Remove the top and bottom from the @courgette{1}(top and bottom removed), quarter lengthways
then chop into 1cm cubes. Halve, then remove the core from the @yellow pepper{1} and chop
into 1cm cubes as well. Put a large #saucepan{} of water with a pinch of @salt{pinch} on
to boil for the pasta.

Heat a splash of @olive oil{1%splash} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat and add the
@beef mince{300%g}. Cook until browned, ~{5%minutes}. Use a #wooden spoon{} to break it
up as it cooks. Once the beef has browned add the @soy sauce{1%tbsp} and
@dried oregano{1%tsp}. Cook for ~{1%minute} more, then add the
@finely chopped tomatoes with onion and garlic{1%400g can}. Bring to the boil.

Add the courgette and pepper, then lower the heat until the ragu is gently bubbling away.
Cook, stirring occasionally until nice and thick and the veggies are soft, ~{15%minutes}.
Taste and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} if necessary.

Meanwhile, add the @spaghetti{200%g} to the pan of boiling water and cook until 'al dente',
about ~{10%minutes}.

> 'Al dente' simply means the pasta is cooked through but has a tiny bit of firmness
> left in the middle.

While the ragu and pasta simmer away, halve the @cherry plum tomatoes{200%g} and pop into
a #bowl{}. Remove the ends from the @cucumber{1/2} and chop into 2cm chunks. Add to the
tomatoes in the bowl. Use half as salad for the kids! Mix the @punchy balsamic mustard{1%tbsp}
with the @olive oil{2%tbsp} and season with a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Use this to dress the
@baby leaf mix{100%g} and remaining tomatoes and cucumber for the adults, just before serving.

Drain the pasta in a #colander{} and toss into the ragu before serving with plenty of
@grated hard Italian style cheese{2%tbsp}.

> Serve the beef ragu on top of the pasta if that's how it's preferred! Pop the salad
> alongside and buon appetito!